00:07:57.800 --> 00:08:00.356
So now that you're convinced
that Material Design is

00:08:00.356 --> 00:08:01.980
something you want
to do with your app,

00:08:01.980 --> 00:08:04.120
how are we going to
go about doing it?

00:08:04.120 --> 00:08:07.580
Well, that's where the Design
Support Library comes in.

00:08:07.580 --> 00:08:12.320
It's part of the support
library family on Android.

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:15.950
It adds support for various
Material Design components

00:08:15.950 --> 00:08:17.910
and patterns for app
developers to build

00:08:17.910 --> 00:08:20.490
upon, such as
navigation drawers,

00:08:20.490 --> 00:08:24.730
floating action buttons,
snackbars, and tabs.

00:08:24.730 --> 00:08:26.620
It also lets you
apply material styles

00:08:26.620 --> 00:08:30.230
to all existing components,
such as EditTexts, CheckBoxes,

00:08:30.230 --> 00:08:31.870
and dialogues.

00:08:31.870 --> 00:08:33.630
And possibly most
importantly, it

00:08:33.630 --> 00:08:36.250
lets you build a
consistent material

00:08:36.250 --> 00:08:43.230
design all the way
back to Android 2.1.

00:08:43.230 --> 00:08:47.200
So to implement this Design
Support Library in your app,

00:08:47.200 --> 00:08:51.237
simply add this dependency
to your gradle build file.

00:08:51.237 --> 00:08:53.570
As you can see, I've listed
other support libraries that

00:08:53.570 --> 00:08:56.680
are available, and these will
help you create a more complete

00:08:56.680 --> 00:08:57.930
material design.

00:08:57.930 --> 00:09:00.990
Such things as CardViews
and RecyclerViews.

00:09:00.990 --> 00:09:03.250
But we're going to focus
just on the Support Design

00:09:03.250 --> 00:09:06.040
Library for now.

00:09:06.040 --> 00:09:09.440
So the first thing you'll do is
set up your application theme.

00:09:09.440 --> 00:09:11.770
And it's important to note
here that we are extending

00:09:11.770 --> 00:09:14.470
the Theme.AppCompat themes.

00:09:14.470 --> 00:09:17.540
And that makes sure that
the material attributes

00:09:17.540 --> 00:09:19.770
are applied to your app.

00:09:19.770 --> 00:09:22.890
And then we'll want to
define a few colours.

00:09:22.890 --> 00:09:27.160
Colour Primary, Primary Dark,
and Colour Accent are the main

00:09:27.160 --> 00:09:30.440
colours that will be used
throughout your app for styling

00:09:30.440 --> 00:09:33.230
and giving colour to
things such as toolbars,

00:09:33.230 --> 00:09:37.345
and action buttons, and
accents to all of the controls.

00:09:40.990 --> 00:09:43.840
We're going to have a quick
look at how to implement

00:09:43.840 --> 00:09:46.885
a few material UI components.

00:09:46.885 --> 00:09:48.510
First one we're going
to have a look at

00:09:48.510 --> 00:09:51.030
is quite a common
pattern where there

00:09:51.030 --> 00:09:55.050
is an AppBar and
flexible space at the top

00:09:55.050 --> 00:09:57.900
of some scrollable
content on your screen.

00:09:57.900 --> 00:10:02.090
As you can see on this slide,
as the user scrolls up,

00:10:02.090 --> 00:10:05.521
the top section gets collapsed
into a more compact version

00:10:05.521 --> 00:10:06.020
of that.

00:10:09.180 --> 00:10:11.170
So to get started,
the first thing

00:10:11.170 --> 00:10:14.340
we need to know a bit about
is the CoordinatorLayout.

00:10:14.340 --> 00:10:16.470
And this is a new layout
that was introduced

00:10:16.470 --> 00:10:18.820
in the Design Support Library.

00:10:18.820 --> 00:10:21.860
And it coordinates
animation behavior

00:10:21.860 --> 00:10:25.060
between views inside of it.

00:10:25.060 --> 00:10:26.960
It's possible to define
your own behaviors,

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:31.157
but basic ones are provided for
floating action bars, AppBars,

00:10:31.157 --> 00:10:31.740
and snackbars.

00:10:34.700 --> 00:10:37.680
So basically, it
lets the views inside

00:10:37.680 --> 00:10:39.690
of that layout interact
with each other

00:10:39.690 --> 00:10:44.790
without those views knowing
too much about the other views.

00:10:44.790 --> 00:10:47.730
Let's get into
our AppBar layout.

00:10:47.730 --> 00:10:51.670
So this XML layout shows
that we have an AppBar layout

00:10:51.670 --> 00:10:52.780
at the top.

00:10:52.780 --> 00:10:56.057
And inside of that, a
CollapsingToolbarLayout.

00:10:56.057 --> 00:10:58.140
And that's the one that's
responsible for actually

00:10:58.140 --> 00:11:03.400
collapsing the space and moving
the views around inside of it.

00:11:03.400 --> 00:11:07.800
Now you can see, we've set
some scroll flags on that view.

00:11:07.800 --> 00:11:12.232
We've set it to scroll
and exit until collapsed.

00:11:12.232 --> 00:11:13.940
And that says that
when the user scrolls,

00:11:13.940 --> 00:11:15.940
that section should also scroll.

00:11:15.940 --> 00:11:18.420
And it should be collapsed
until the user starts

00:11:18.420 --> 00:11:20.700
scrolling back down again.

00:11:20.700 --> 00:11:24.400
And inside of that layout we
have two views-- an image view

00:11:24.400 --> 00:11:25.380
and a toolbar.

00:11:25.380 --> 00:11:29.310
The image view is acting as a
flexible space in this example.

00:11:29.310 --> 00:11:33.390
And the toolbar will
be pinned at the top.

00:11:33.390 --> 00:11:37.690
And let's set the collapse mode
to pin so it will stay there.

00:11:37.690 --> 00:11:39.430
And on the image view,
our collapse mode

00:11:39.430 --> 00:11:40.540
is set to parallax.

00:11:40.540 --> 00:11:43.000
And that means it will scroll
with a parallax effect,

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.566
slightly slower than
the content below it.

00:11:48.458 --> 00:11:51.580
And that's all you need
to implement that pattern.

00:11:51.580 --> 00:11:53.900
It's quite straightforward.

00:11:53.900 --> 00:11:56.550
Next we'll look at the
Floating Action Button.

00:11:56.550 --> 00:11:59.500
And just as a reminder,
that's the circular button

00:11:59.500 --> 00:12:02.940
that's used to promote a
primary action on your screen.

00:12:02.940 --> 00:12:04.940
It's usually anchored
to one of the corners

00:12:04.940 --> 00:12:10.350
or sides of the screen or
along the seam of two views.

00:12:10.350 --> 00:12:12.710
To implement it is
quite straightforward.

00:12:12.710 --> 00:12:15.560
We simply implement a
FloatingActionButton view.

00:12:15.560 --> 00:12:19.110
And this extends an image for
you so you can use it in a way

00:12:19.110 --> 00:12:20.370
that you're familiar with.

00:12:20.370 --> 00:12:22.328
But there are a couple
of attributes that we'll

00:12:22.328 --> 00:12:23.250
look at specifically.

00:12:23.250 --> 00:12:26.380
And that's the layout gravity,
which lets us anchor that

00:12:26.380 --> 00:12:29.160
to the side of our layout.

00:12:29.160 --> 00:12:30.570
And also the FAB size.

00:12:30.570 --> 00:12:34.920
We have two options there, the
normal size or a mini size.

00:12:34.920 --> 00:12:36.860
And as you can see, we've
included this inside

00:12:36.860 --> 00:12:39.740
of our CoordinatorLayout
because that lets

00:12:39.740 --> 00:12:42.066
us interact with other views.

00:12:42.066 --> 00:12:43.940
So we're going to have
a quick look at adding

00:12:43.940 --> 00:12:46.540
a snackbar to the set up.

00:12:46.540 --> 00:12:48.320
Now the animation
you'll see on this slide

00:12:48.320 --> 00:12:50.830
shows that when the
snackbar comes up,

00:12:50.830 --> 00:12:54.770
it actually moves the floating
action button with it.

00:12:54.770 --> 00:12:58.250
So, snackbar is like a
toast, except it forms

00:12:58.250 --> 00:12:59.490
part of the view hierarchy.

00:12:59.490 --> 00:13:04.570
So it actually interacts
as part of your view.

00:13:04.570 --> 00:13:06.610
And what we've got here,
this little bit of code

00:13:06.610 --> 00:13:09.240
is to say when the Floating
Action Button is pressed,

00:13:09.240 --> 00:13:12.520
simply create a
snackbar and show it.

00:13:12.520 --> 00:13:14.650
And that's what you're
seeing in the animation.

00:13:14.650 --> 00:13:16.430
And because those
two views are inside

00:13:16.430 --> 00:13:21.020
of the same Coordinator Layout,
they interact with each other.

00:13:21.020 --> 00:13:24.080
And that's a Coordinator Layout
in action using the default

00:13:24.080 --> 00:13:27.980
behaviors of those two views.

00:13:27.980 --> 00:13:31.060
One more pattern is
the Navigation Drawer,

00:13:31.060 --> 00:13:32.760
that you should
be familiar with.

00:13:32.760 --> 00:13:34.840
It's a flexible
navigation pattern,

00:13:34.840 --> 00:13:37.210
and it usually slides
in from the left.

00:13:37.210 --> 00:13:38.770
As you can see in
this screenshot,

00:13:38.770 --> 00:13:41.450
it has a section at
the top where you can

00:13:41.450 --> 00:13:42.680
put anything you want in it.

00:13:42.680 --> 00:13:46.017
And then the navigation
items below that.

00:13:46.017 --> 00:13:48.100
And we've actually got it
separated with sub-items

00:13:48.100 --> 00:13:49.350
in this one.

00:13:49.350 --> 00:13:52.820
So let's have a quick look at
how we will implement that.

00:13:52.820 --> 00:13:56.620
First, you'll see on the
left we have the XML layout.

00:13:56.620 --> 00:14:00.880
At the top level of our layout,
we have the drawer layout.

00:14:00.880 --> 00:14:03.380
And inside of it,
as the last child,

00:14:03.380 --> 00:14:05.590
we add the new NavigationView.

00:14:05.590 --> 00:14:09.250
And that is effectively a
drawer that will slide out.

00:14:09.250 --> 00:14:12.460
And we've added special
properties to that.

00:14:12.460 --> 00:14:15.440
The Header Layout, which can
be any XML layout that gets

00:14:15.440 --> 00:14:20.250
inflated into that properties
section of the page view.

00:14:20.250 --> 00:14:22.950
And then we also have
the menu [? attribute. ?]

00:14:22.950 --> 00:14:24.930
And that will look
for an XML menu

00:14:24.930 --> 00:14:28.240
file that we've defined on
the right of this slide.

00:14:28.240 --> 00:14:31.450
And that defines the
groups and items that

00:14:31.450 --> 00:14:33.050
are in the navigation drawer.

00:14:33.050 --> 00:14:35.940
And you can see that
we've got one group there

00:14:35.940 --> 00:14:37.790
and multiple items inside of it.

00:14:37.790 --> 00:14:41.020
And for each item, we can define
the icon that's displayed,

00:14:41.020 --> 00:14:45.340
and also the title of
the text is displayed.

00:14:45.340 --> 00:14:47.590
So with those two files
and the Header Layout,

00:14:47.590 --> 00:14:52.590
you can very quickly get a
Navigation Drawer in place.

00:14:52.590 --> 00:14:54.390
So if you've been
